continuous \u0027machinery-like\u0027 murmur best heard in the left infraclavicular area. The infant was born at term with no complications during pregnancy or delivery. Vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patent ductus arteriosus","Tetralogy of Fallot","Coarctation of aorta","Atrial septal defect","Ventricular septal defect"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe continuous \u0027machinery\u0027 murmur in the left upper chest is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Epatent ductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs when the ductus arteriosus fails to close after birth, allowing blood to flow from the aorta to the pulmonary artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach of the other congenital cardiac conditions has distinct auscultatory findings: \u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E produces a harsh systolic ejection murmur with cyanosis. \u003Cstrong\u003ECoarctation of aorta\u003C/strong\u003E causes blood pressure differences between upper and lower limbs with a systolic murmur heard posteriorly. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E creates a fixed split second heart sound with a systolic flow murmur. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E produces a harsh holosystolic murmur at the left sternal border.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patent ductus arteriosus presents with a continuous \u0027machinery\u0027 murmur best heard in the left upper chest.","The ductus arteriosus normally closes within 24-48 hours after birth in term infants.","Patent ductus arteriosus results in left-to-right shunting of blood from the aorta to the pulmonary artery."],"references":["Dice JE, Bhatia J. Patent ductus arteriosus: an overview. J Pediatr Pharmacol Ther. 2007 Jul;12(3):138-46. doi: 10.5863/1551-6776-12.3.138. PMID: 23055849; PMCID: PMC3462096.","Gillam-Krakauer M, Mahajan K. Patent Ductus Arteriosus. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613509.","Topol, E. J., \u0026 Califf, R. M. (Eds.). (2007). Textbook of cardiovascular medicine. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74322"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15514"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74322"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T22:29:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T22:30:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8205"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"